snippet.textDisplay:
At least the prequels were planned from the beginning, this movie is bad only because of the bad things that happened in the previous two films. I like this movie much much better than TFA and TLJ, but I don't think its better as a trilogy than the Prequels due to the simple fact that they connected in a way that didn't make sense. Its obvious that this is a horribly planned trilogy and if JJ Abrams were to have directed the Last Jedi, it probably would be a much more fluid trilogy.

I acknowledge that the prequels have horrible dialogue. Boring exposition. A few bad characters (JarJar especially, Young Anakin), but to throw away the prequels like garbage is wrong. They still have a great overall story with a mediocre execution. But this trilogy has a mediocre plot with terrible execution. There is no interest from me, and I like the prequels much more than this movie trilogy.

snippet.textDisplay: This new trilogy of films has been so disgraceful that it has made people appreciate the once despised Prequels more than ever. From the Force Awakens there were so many problems with worldbuilding that we have absolutely no idea what the state of the galaxy is like. There is no explanation for how we have a complete reversion back to decades prior where the Empire is basically back in power under a new name. However, at least the Force Awakens set up questions that could have satisfying answers in Episode 8. Then the Last Jedi came out and nuked the franchise. Not only did nothing that happened in the plot make a lick of sense, but those set ups in the Force Awakens were destroyed. We were told that they didn’t matter, that we shouldn’t have cared about them in the first place, and that all of those questions had the same answer: nothing. Who was Snoke? Who were Rey’s parents and how is she so ridiculously powerful? What was Luke doing on that island for all those years? Are the Knights of Ren still a relevant thing? Rian Johnson insulted us for caring about things that were set up in the previous movie for the purpose of “subverting expectations.” Yeah, I expected a good movie and I was certainly subverted. By the time Rise of Skywalker rolled around, anticipation was at an all time low for Star Wars. Instead of “I can’t wait to see how it ends!” the attitude was “let’s get this shit over with.” And sure enough, the film spent a lot of time undoing what the previous movie had done. We still got a terrible ending to an awful and unnecessary trilogy, but at least those jabs at TLJ were fun to watch and laugh at. Star Wars has been dethroned by the MCU as the world’s most appreciated fictional series because Disney has handled this trilogy so poorly and haphazardly. It’s like a nightmare I can’t wake up from and the only thing I can do is tell myself that these stories are not canon, but unfortunately that nightmare is the reality of the situation.
